
# Lab 2: DHCP and IP Address Verification (macOS)

## Objective

The objective of this lab was to verify DHCP functionality and identify the IPv4 address assigned to my device using macOS terminal commands.

This demonstrates basic network troubleshooting skills required in a Help Desk role.

---

## Tools Used

- macOS Terminal
- ifconfig command
- ipconfig command

---

## Commands Executed

### Check network interface configuration

```bash

ifconfig en0

Output

inet 192.168.1.134 netmask 0xffffff00 broadcast 192.168.1.255

Analysis

• The presence of an IPv4 address (192.168.1.134) confirms DHCP successfully assigned an IP address.

• This indicates proper communication between the client machine and DHCP server (router).

• The network interface status was "active," confirming Layer 1 and Layer 2 connectivity.


This lab taught me how to:

  Identify IPv4 vs IPv6 addresses

  Verify DHCP functionality

  Use terminal commands to troubleshoot network connectivity

  Confirm network interface status

Real-World Help Desk Application

  If a user cannot connect to the network, checking for a valid IPv4 address helps determine whether DHCP is functioning properly.

  If the system shows a 169.254.x.x address, it indicates DHCP failure.
